{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540035","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540035"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:49:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16731"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16731"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.21,0.09,0.05,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66639"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9422"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4113"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22285"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43649"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66639"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic two weeks after an uncomplicated vaginal delivery of her second child. She is exclusively breastfeeding and wishes to discuss contraceptive options. She is interested in having a progesterone intrauterine contraceptive device inserted. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her uterus is well involuted and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate timing for intrauterine contraceptive insertion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wait until menses resume","Immediate insertion today","Wait until 4-6 months postpartum","Wait until breastfeeding ceases","Wait until 4-8 weeks postpartum"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case addresses the optimal timing of intrauterine contraceptive (IUC) insertion in the postpartum period. The timing of insertion is crucial for both safety and effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaiting until 4-8 weeks postpartum\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate option. After 4 weeks, the uterus has largely completed its involution, and the risk of perforation returns to baseline. This timing provides a good balance between early contraceptive coverage and safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate insertion today\u003C/strong\u003E (at 2 weeks postpartum) falls within the high-risk window of 48 hours to 4 weeks postpartum. During this time, the uterus is still involuting, and the risk of perforation is significantly increased, particularly in breastfeeding women.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no need to \u003Cstrong\u003Ewait until 4-6 months postpartum\u003C/strong\u003E as this unnecessarily delays contraception. The uterus has completed its involution well before this time, and there is no additional benefit to such a long delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaiting until breastfeeding ceases\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary. While breastfeeding is associated with a higher risk of perforation during the 48-hour to 4-week window, once past 4 weeks postpartum, IUC can be safely inserted regardless of breastfeeding status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWaiting until menses resume\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary and could leave the patient without effective contraception for many months, particularly while breastfeeding. IUC can be safely inserted after 4 weeks postpartum regardless of menstrual status, provided pregnancy has been excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe only times when IUC insertion is recommended in the postpartum period are either within 48 hours of delivery (immediate post-placental insertion) or after 4 weeks postpartum. The period between 48 hours and 4 weeks should be avoided due to the increased risk of uterine perforation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone intrauterine contraception insertion between 48 hours and 4 weeks postpartum carries increased risk of uterine perforation.","Immediate postpartum IUC insertion (within 48 hours) or delayed insertion (minimum 4 weeks) are the recommended timeframes.","Breastfeeding is associated with higher risk of uterine perforation during IUC insertion but overall risk is low if \u003E28 days"],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception: Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:44:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T17:45:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9422"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisi